description.en: For the purposes of regulating the conditions of operation of vehicles on roads, a road vehicle is a motorised or non-motorised vehicle which is constructed for use on roads for the carriage of persons, animals or goods.
A special vehicle is a vehicle manufactured for purposes other than road traffic, which may be operated on roads if conditions are met.
A vehicle is a machine, usually with wheels and an engine, used for transporting people or goods, especially on land.

A vehicle category is a group of vehicles which have the same technical conditions laid down in an implementing regulation. Road vehicles and special vehicles are divided into categories L, M, N, O, T, C, R, S and Z.
A trailer is a non-motorised road vehicle intended to be towed by another vehicle to which it is coupled in a combination.
A road vehicle with width or length exceeding 1.4 m, design speed exceeding 15 km.h-1 or maximum permissible weight exceeding 450 kg.
A motorised vehicle is a vehicle with an engine.
A non-motorised vehicle is a vehicle without an engine.
A vehicle designed primarily for driving on snow.
A vehicle designed primarily for off-road driving.

Vehicle system means any structural system of a vehicle which is subject to the technical requirements laid down in an implementing regulation. An example of a vehicle system is brakes or emission reduction devices.

A structural component of a vehicle is a component of the vehicle which must be type-approved independently of the vehicle if so provided for in the implementing legislation and which is subject to the technical requirements laid down in the implementing legislation. An example of a structural component of a vehicle is a lamp.

A manufacturer is a person who manufactures a vehicle, its system, component or separate technical unit or has it designed or manufactured and markets it under his own name or trademark or uses it for his own account.

A road vehicle technical inspection is an inspection of its roadworthiness which includes the technical condition and functioning of a road vehicle, its systems, components and separate technical units and their environmental impact or a registration test of a road vehicle.

A separate technical unit of a vehicle is a component, the type of which may be approved independently of the vehicle but only in relation to one or more vehicle types, if so provided for in the implementing legislation, and which is subject to the technical requirements laid down in the implementing legislation. An independent technical unit of a vehicle is, for example, the rear bumper of a vehicle, or a fixed or swap body of a vehicle.

description.en: An incomplete vehicle is any vehicle that must undergo at least one further stage of completion in order to meet the relevant technical requirements.

A road vehicle is technically fit for use on the road if no defects or only minor defects have been found during the road vehicle technical inspection. If the technical inspection has revealed minor defects, the operator of the road vehicle shall remedy them.

A road vehicle is technically fit for use only for 30 days from the date of the technical inspection, if a technical inspection detects a serious defect. Within this period, the operator of the road vehicle shall be obliged to bring the road vehicle with the rectified serious defect to the technical inspection station for a repeat technical inspection.

description.en: A road vehicle is technically unfit for use and must not be used in traffic when a technical inspection of a road vehicle reveals a dangerous defect, the operator of the road vehicle did not bring the road vehicle with the rectified serious defect to the technical inspection station for a repeat technical inspection in the period of 30 days from the date of the technical inspection where the serious defect was detected, or if the repeated technical inspection reveals that the defect to be rectified has been recurrently rectified.
